Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Toss @cauliflower florets{10%oz} with @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}, a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{4%tsp}, and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{} in a #medium bowl{}. Transfer to a #baking sheet{} and bake until browned and crisp, about ~{25%minutes}.

> TIP: Don't worry if a few crumbs fall off.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @red onion{1}. Mince or grate @garlic{1%clove} (use the other clove as you like).

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add onion and cook until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}, tossing occasionally. Stir in @balsamic vinegar{1%tbsp} and reduce heat to low. Cook until very soft, about ~{10%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Remove from pan and set aside.

Shape @Pat LaFrieda hamburger blend{10%oz} into two patties with your hands (you'll want them to be slightly wider than the buns). Season with @dried oregano{1%tsp}, salt, and pepper. Carefully wipe out pan you cooked onions in with a #paper towel{}, then heat a drizzle of oil in it over medium-high heat. Add patties and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

> TIP: Got a grill? Fire it up! The burgers will taste great cooked on the grates. Place them over direct heat and grill to your desired doneness, 3-5 minutes per side. You can even toast the buns on there, too.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{1%tbsp} and a pinch of @garlic{}. Season with @salt{}, @pepper{}, and more garlic (to taste). Split @brioche buns{2} in half, place on another baking sheet, and toast in oven until golden brown, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Spread aioli on buns, then fill each with a burger and some onion. Serve with cauliflower on the side.